metadata.name: Richter #95
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press “s” to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

leanderherzog.ch/2023/richter/
leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #247
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Punktwelt #516
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ’s’ to save a png. Press ’4’ to export a high resolution png. Press ’8’ to export a very high resolution png. Press ’e’ to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: Atmosphere #102
metadata.description:
Atmosphere is a 3D interactive and generative piece creating an organic cube or sphere.  You can turn around and zoom in or let it live.
The size, position and frequency of shapes are generated for each token, along with the color theme.  Movements and positions are generated by a noise and a seed, it’s the same for each view.

 On live version the visual fit your screen.

Shortcuts on live version :
	- press ‘p’ to stop the motion and explore
	- press ‘f’ to launch the fullscreen mode
	- press ‘h’ to hide the cursor and `cmd/ctrl + s` to save a PNG.

Features :
	- Duo tone - Theme has 2 colors
	- Direction - Direction of the movements of shapes (x, y, none or all)
	- Rotation - Rotation of shapes (x,z, all or none)
	- Main Shape - sphere or box
	- Shapes - cylinder, cube, plane or torus 
	- Scalable - If the  motion impact the scale of shapes or not

Created by Quentin Hocdé, in Brussels (Belgium).

metadata.name: PEGS #422
metadata.description: Taking inspiration from work by Karl Gerstner, Armin Hofmann, Nick Kuder and Dmitri Cherniak, PEGS explores the limits of constrained algorithmic variation. Based on the simple, playful idea of wrapping a string across a board of pegs, it shows how endless possibilities can be achieved with just a basic set of rules and a few primary colors. When done right, generative art challenges us to answer fundamental questions around creativity, beauty, and life itself.

metadata.name: Alma de Flor #18
metadata.description:
Alma de Flor is a project inspired by nature and floral afterlife. 

Plants are alive, they grow on our planet and populate almost every continent on earth. 
They live, grow and die. 
Some plants live a long time, some others don't. Kind of like humans, they change and evolve. They have souls, but they're different from ours, they differ in energy. 

Living in a tropical country allowed me to live in a place with huge biodiversity, so for me, this is how a born European, raised Latino person connects with this feeling.
